### Gay-Lussac's Law: temperature-pressure relationship

* Gay-Lussac's Law states that the pressure of a fixed amount of gas (\(n\) is constant) maintained at constant volume is directly proportional to its absolute temperature (in Kelvin).

Mathematically, \(p\,\alpha\,\mathrm{T}\) or \(\frac{\mathbf{p}}{\mathrm{T}}=\mathrm{constant}\) (constant n and V)

Comparing the temperature and pressure of a given amount of a gas **under two different sets of conditions at constant volume**, the following equation is applicable.

\(\frac{P_{i}}{\mathrm{T}_{i}}=\frac{P_{i}}{\mathrm{T}_{r}}\)

Graphical representations (at fixed V):

* Application of Gay-Lussac's Law:
* Shooting of a gun
* As gunpowder burns, it creates superheated gas, which forces the bullet out of the gun barrel.
* Pumping Car Tires

In temperate countries, car tire pressures need to be checked in winter. This is because with the low temperatures in the winter months, car tires could be underinflated due to a drop in gas pressure. Driving under such conditions could reduce tire durability and fuel economy of the car.

Similarly, in tropical countries, car tires should only be pumped or checked in the morning and not after a long drive. This is because after travelling for some time, the temperature of the tires will increase, causing an increase in gas pressure.

### Combined Gas Law

* Mathematically, in combining Boyle's Law (\(V\propto\frac{1}{p}\)), Charles's Law (\(V\propto T\)) and Gay-Lussac's Law (\(p\propto T\)): \[V\propto\frac{T}{p}\qquad\qquad\text{(constant n)}\] \[V=k\frac{T}{p}\] \[\frac{PV}{T}=k\quad\text{where $k$ is a constant}\]
* Comparing the properties of a gas under all three conditions of pressure, volume and temperature, the following equation is applicable when the **amount of gaseous particles remains unchanged**.

\[\frac{p_{i}V_{i}}{T_{i}}=\frac{p_{i}V_{i}}{T_{i}}\]
* Hence, the quantitative effect of the gas can be calculated _when two quantities of the gas are varied at the same time_.

### Avogadro's Law: quantity-volume relationship

* Avogadro's Law states that _at constant temperature and pressure_, _the volume of a gas is directly proportional to the number of moles of the gas_.

\[\text{Mathematically,}\qquad\qquad\text{V $\alpha$ n}\qquad\text{or}\qquad\qquad\text{V $= constant $\times$ n}\]
* It then follows that _equal volumes of gases contain the same number of gas particles_ under constant T and \(p\) (Avogadro's Hypothesis). Therefore, \(\Rightarrow\) 1 mole of **any** gas will occupy the same volume! \(\Rightarrow\) Recap: molar gas volume, \(V_{m}\) At 0 \({}^{\circ}\)C (273 K) and 1 bar or 1 x 10\({}^{5}\) Pa (s.t.p.), 1 mole of any gas occupies a volume of **22.7 dm\({}^{3}\)**. \(\circ\) At 20 \({}^{\circ}\)C (293 K) and 1 atm or 101325 Pa (r.t.p.), 1 mole of any gas occupies a volume of **24.0 dm\({}^{3}\)**.
* Application of Avogadro's Law: When blowing a balloon, its size increases because more gaseous particles are being introduced into the balloon at constant external pressure and temperature.

## 3 Ideal Gas Equation

* The gas laws are: Boyle's law: V \(\alpha\) \(\frac{1}{P}\) (constant n, T) Charles's law: V \(\alpha\) T (constant n, \(p\)) Gay-Lussac's law: \(p\) \(\alpha\) T (constant n, V) Avogadro's law: V \(\alpha\) n (constant \(p\), T)
